This really isn't a Deno specific question or problem. This would be the behaviour of any TypeScript project running in strict mode with `allowJs` enabled, which is the default for Deno TypeScript type checking.

You can use [JSDoc](https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/jsdoc-supported-types.html) annotations in JavaScript to assign types:

```js
/** @type {any} */
const x = {x: 2};
x.y = 3;
export { x };
```

This is not a Deno issue, it has to do with module instantiation order with ES modules.  The modules you are importing get instantiated before the module that imports it, meaning the code in the imported module runs before the code in the `main.ts`.

If you want something like this to work, you need to create something like `globals.ts`:

```ts
globalThis.document = {} as any;
```

And then in your `main.ts`:

```ts
import "./globals.ts";


import {
  attr,
  customElement,
  FASTElement,
  html,
  Observable,
} from "https://cdn.skypack.dev/@microsoft/fast-element?dts";
```

