In my opinion there's only a few places where non-arrow-syntax functions are necessary and top-level is not one of them. The example @cjihrig linked is somewhat applicable, however this is not a top-level function, it's an object property assignment, to create a method on the `ReadStream` class prototype.

As soon as you use `this` in a top level function in ES6, you're doing something wrong in my eyes, because that's what classes are for. And if you actually want to refer to `window` or `globalThis` with your `this` in your arrow function, you should just use `window` or `globalThis` for better readability anyways.

The only places where I don't use arrow functions is where I can't: `constructor`, getter and setters, generator functions and class methods defined outside of the class body. The beauty about arrow functions is that they effectively fixed `this` in JS, because the `this` in arrow functions will always just refer to the `this` in the scope above and not sometimes to the function itself, other times to the class it is defined in, etc.

Arrow functions also follow the syntax of the rest of the language, where `x = y` means `y` is assigned to the `x` variable, while the `function` keyword somehow is able to the same without ever using the `=` symbol. For the same reason I'm writing classes in a somewhat unconvential but not less comprehensible way:

```js
const MyClass = class {
    // ...
};
```

instead of

```js
class MyClass {
    // ...
};
```
