@NitishKumar525 The Typescript compiler does not track dependencies between different variables in this way, so it doesn't "remember" that a.type and b.type are equal, for instance. This has been variously requested as a feature, but e.g. [this issue](https://github.com/microsoft/TypeScript/issues/54252) shows the Typescript team don't currently consider it worth implementing.

If it was my code, I would probably write it this way:

```bash
 switch (a.type) {
    case "A": {
      return b.type === "A" && a.propsOfA === b.propsOfA;
    }
    case "B": {
      return b.type === "B" && a.propsOfB === b.propsOfB;
    }
    case "C": {
      return b.type === "C" && a.propsOfC === b.propsOfC;
    }
  }
```

That's three checks instead of nine. However, this might look inelegant since `a.type === b.type` is one check rather than three. An alternative approach is to construct a version of the union type where it's OK to write `b.propsOfA` without narrowing on `b.type === "A"`:

```bash
 interface A {
    type: "A";
    propsOfA: string;
    propsOfB?: never;
    propsOfC?: never;
}

interface B {
    type: "B";
    propsOfA?: never;
    propsOfB: number;
    propsOfC?: never;
}

interface C {
    type: "C";
    propsOfA?: never;
    propsOfB?: never;
    propsOfC: boolean;
}
```

With the types declared this way, your original code compiles with no errors. This is also actually a little safer than the original version, since it forbids objects like `{type: "A", propsOfA: "foo", propsOfC: true}` which are assignable to the original type `A`.

If the above is too much to write out manually, you can also construct these types programmatically:

```bash
/**
 * Makes a discriminated union type "safe" by requiring properties specific
 * to some branches to be absent in other branches.
 */
type SafeUnion<T> = Simplify<T> extends infer _T ? _T extends unknown ? Replace<{[K in AnyKeyOf<T>]?: never}, _T> : never : never

/**
 * Simplifies a type to make it more readable.
 */
type Simplify<T> = T extends unknown ? {[K in keyof T]: T[K]} : never

/**
 * Similar to an intersection `S & T`, except shared properties take their
 * types only from `T`.
 */
type Replace<S, T> = Simplify<T & Omit<S, keyof T>>

/**
 * The keys of any member of a union type.
 */
type AnyKeyOf<T> = T extends unknown ? keyof T : never
```

Then your code can be written like:

```
type ABC = SafeUnion<A | B | C>

function isEqual(a: ABC, b: ABC) {
    // ...
}
```
